This study compared the effects of a physical activity promotion program (PAPP) with a control group that did not perform the program. A total of 100 participants, both genders, aged 55 and older from Torremolinos, Spain, were randomly selected and divided into two groups of 50 each. The PAPP group received the program for 60 minutes, twice a week, for three months. The control group received health education. The effectiveness of the intervention was measured by the Short Form 12 health survey questionnaire and the EuroQoL-5D questionnaire. Cardiopulmonary function was measured with a spirometry and a walking test according to the Bruce protocol.

The results showed that the PAPP had a significant impact on the quality of life in men, leading to an increase. However, the quality of life in women did not improve. The average changes in the lung and cardiovascular function were not significant between groups.

In conclusion, the PAPP had a positive effect on the quality of life in men, while the cardiopulmonary function results were not as relevant.&lt;/s&gt;&lt;s&gt;

This study aimed to determine the effectiveness of a physiotherapist-prescribed exercise programme focused on knee joint strength and control in reducing knee pain in children with Joint Hypermobility Syndrome (JHS). The study also looked at whether the range in which these exercises are performed affects outcomes.

The results showed that children with JHS and knee pain, who were randomly assigned to the hypermobile range exercise group, experienced significant improvements in knee pain, as measured by a visual analogue scale. In addition, parents of these children reported improved psychosocial health, specifically self-esteem, mental health and behaviour, when compared to the neutral range exercise group. No adverse events occurred and no other differences were found between groups.

The study concluded that a physiotherapist-prescribed, supervised, individualised and progressed exercise programme focused on knee joint strength and control is effective in reducing knee pain in children with JHS, and that exercising into the hypermobile range may be beneficial for psychosocial health, while exercising to neutral only may be beneficial for physical health.&lt;/s&gt;&lt;s&gt;
